How does age relate to attrition?

ID="Age"
yes=casedata[,sum(Attrition=="Yes"),ID]; colnames(yes)[2]="Yes"
no=casedata[,sum(Attrition=="No"),ID];   colnames(no)[2]="No"
temp=merge(yes,no,all=T)
temp=melt(temp,id=ID)
temp=as.data.frame(temp)
colnames(temp)=c(ID,"Attrition","Count")
temp %>% ggplot(aes(fill=Attrition,y=Count,x=eval(as.symbol(ID))))+geom_bar(stat="identity")+xlab(ID)

Here we can see that attrition is greatest between 29 and 35. Here we see that attrition is greater at earlier ages, with a noticeable peak at age 58.

##    Age Attrition Count Total Proportion
## 81  58       Yes     5    14  0.3571429
## 82  58        No     9    14  0.6428571

How does business travel relate to attrition?

Here we can see that attrition, proportionally, is greatest for employees who travel frequently and the least for employees who do not travel. ### Automatically detecting single predictors We can go on and on plotting individual predictors, but lets try to automate the process. This R code will go through every numeric variable and see if they can predict attrition.
